{
  "doc_id": "26412",
  "text": "We propose an additional mechanism in which Tax can function to alter cell cycle progression, through the upregulation of both p21/waf1 and cyclin D2, promoting the formation of highly active kinase complexes. Our laboratory and others have shown that in HTLV-1 infected cells and Tax expressing cells, cyclin D2 and p21/waf1 levels are upregulated through Tax transactivation [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . The role of cyclin D2 in promoting tumorigenesis is easily understood as it functions to phosphorylate Rb. It therefore follows that if there are more active cyclin D2/cdk4 complexes available to phosphorylate Rb, the faster the cell can progress through the G 1 phase of the cell cycle. The role of p21/waf1, on the other hand, is less easily understood and seems to be in conflict with the tumorigenic role of Tax. As an inhibitor of cyclin/cdk complexes it would be expected that p21/waf1 would slow down the cell cycle or even cause a G 1 /S block. During preparation of this manuscript, Kawata et al. [CITATION_6] published a report showing the importance of p21/waf1 for Tax-mediated transformation. They showed that when p21/waf1 was co-expressed with Tax in Rat-1 fibroblasts, colony formation in soft agar was increased. In addition, they also showed that p21/waf1 protects Tax expressing Rat-1 cells from apoptosis. This recent paper highlights the importance of p21/waf1 in the transformation and survival of cells. Our study of p21/waf1 has led to an alternative view of p21/waf1 as an activator/assembly factor, rather than a traditional cdk inhibitor in HTLV-1 infected cells, providing an additional explanation for Tax mediated overexpression of p21/waf1 in infected cells.",
